    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a potent offensive profile anchored by **Junior Caminero** (76.66) and **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (75.48), our strongest plays of the day. **Junior Caminero** benefits from an ideal confluence of variables: a favorable matchup against Keller, and, crucially, wind blowing out to add 5% to his power projection. Meanwhile, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** remains a high-upside start despite hitting 8th; his elite sprint speed makes him a priority in our SB-starved Roto context, and his projection is boosted by a 14% dynamic platoon advantage. We also expect strong production from **Trea Turner** (69.15) and **Yordan Alvarez** (67.90) at the top of the order, both of whom carry high-floor xwOBA metrics that mitigate the risk posed by their respective starting pitchers.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Josh Smith**, who sits at 40.62. While he draws a significant 14% boost from a dynamic platoon advantage against Woo, he ultimately failed to crack the starting nine because his raw efficiency couldn't surpass the higher-ceiling outcomes projected for **Chase Meidroth** (66.48) and **Carson Benge** (63.27). **Chase Meidroth** serves as a vital anchor today, as his leadoff spot and 10% batting order bonus make him a more reliable producer than **Josh Smith** in this specific lineup configuration.\n\nWe are proceeding with caution regarding **Dillon Dingler** (48.35), whose score is suppressed by a difficult matchup against Crochet (xERA 2.86). Despite the significant 14% dynamic platoon edge, we are monitoring the catcher position closely for potential defensive substitutions that could limit his plate appearances. As a reminder, **Christian Yelich** remains sidelined, and both **Zac Veen** and **Colt Keith** are unavailable, leaving us with a shallow bench to rotate should mid-game adjustments be required for players like **Victor Scott II**, whose low score (47.23) reflects a tough draw against Burrows and an unfavorable 9-hole assignment.",
